\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_H::1><$Scr_Ps::0>
\f1\b\fs36 Import and Split\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_H::1><!$Scr_Ps::0>
\f1\fs28 Perhaps you have already written a long document and you want to bring it into Scrivener and break it up into smaller sections. You could do that by importing it following the steps above and then using the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scrivlnk://E8AD5C94-F2A4-4BCC-A854-E672C9BDECE8"}}{\fldrslt Split at Selection}} feature. Another option is to use 
\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f2\b Import and Split
\f0\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f1\fs28 :\
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	1.	}From the main menu, select 
\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f2\b Files > Import > Import and Split\'85
\f0\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f1\fs28 \
{\listtext	2.	}In the browser that appears, select the file that you wish to import.\
{\listtext	3.	}In the \'93Sections are separated by\'94 box, enter the text that represents splits in your document. For instance, you could use 
\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f2\b Insert > Break > Page Break
\f0\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f1\fs28  to enter a page break character in here and have your document split at each new page. Or you could enter a couple of return characters, or a separator character you have used in the text (e.g. \'93#\'94).\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1120\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	4.	}For Final Draft files, you can choose which script element to split sections at\'97you will usually want to leave this as \'93Scene Heading\'94.\
{\listtext	5.	}Click \'93Import\'94.\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Your text will now be imported as multiple documents. Go through them and do any necessary clean-up. You can split them further using the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scrivlnk://E8AD5C94-F2A4-4BCC-A854-E672C9BDECE8"}}{\fldrslt Split at Selection}} feature.}